04449nam a22007095i 9780813550343DE-B159720191221113333.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191221s2010    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135503437 a10.36019/97808135503432doi  a(DE-B1597)529978  a(OCoLC)1119149586  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aREL0000002bisacsh1 aStavans, Ilan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut.10aWith All Thine Heart :bLove and the Bible /cMordecai Drache, Ilan Stavans. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2010] 4cÂ©2010  a1 online resource (190 p.) :b10 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tShema Ysrael! -- tI. Adam's Partners: "It is not good for man to be alone" -- tII. The Mission of Abraham: "And I will bless them" -- tIII. The Birth of Israel: "Thou shalt serve thy brother" -- tIV. Moses' Guidance: "If I have found favor in your sight" -- tV. The National Self: "To teach them war" -- tVI. Song of Songs: "Let him kiss me" -- tVII. Job's Perplexity: "A perfect and an upright man" -- tLove and Stupidity -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex -- tAbout the Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIs the Bible actually a love story between a deity and a people? And what does this love story have to do with the modern world? In With All Thine Heart distinguished cultural critic Ilan Stavans speaks to freelance writer Mordecai Drache about love in the Bible. Presented in an engaging, conversational format and touched with striking artwork, the textured dialogue between Stavans and Drache is meant to show how the Bible is a multidimensional text and one that, when considered over the course of history, still has the power to shape our world. The theme of love provides the connective tissue that binds this work. Addressing a wide range of topics, from biblical archaeology and fundamentalism to Hollywood movies, lexicography, and the act of praying, With All Thine Heart suggests that the Hebrew Bible is a novel worth decoding patiently, such as one does with classics like Don Quixote de la Mancha, In Search of Lost Time, and Anna Karenina.  Similar to the protagonists in these tales, biblical characters, although not shaped with the artistic nuance of modern literature, allow for astonishing insight. This exploration of love through the pages of the Bible-organized chronologically from Genesis to Exodus and followed by insightful meditations on the Song of Songs and the Book of Job-is a  delightful intellectual and spiritual treat . . . Shema Ysrael!  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh1 aDrache, Mordecai, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813550343423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813550343.jpg  a978-3-11-066331-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-068861-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG